            <td>30g/week</td>
            <td>Inefficient saturation pattern</td>
            <td>Suboptimal vs daily</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The takeaway is simple: take 3-5g every single day, including rest days, vacation days, and "I'm not training today" days. The saturation effect is what produces benefits, and saturation requires daily input.</p>

    <!-- TIMING AROUND THE MENSTRUAL CYCLE -->
    <h2>Should Women Adjust Creatine Timing Around the Menstrual Cycle?</h2>

    <p>An emerging area of interest is whether creatine effectiveness varies across menstrual cycle phases. The current evidence suggests modest variation, with creatine showing potentially enhanced benefits during the late luteal phase (premenstrual phase) when hormonal shifts increase metabolic demand.</p>

    <p>Practically, this does not require changing timing or dose across the cycle. Take 3-5g daily regardless of cycle phase. Some women report subjectively stronger benefits during the late luteal phase, but no formal recommendation requires cycle-specific dosing adjustment.</p>

    <p>For women using cycle tracking apps to optimize training and supplementation, creatine fits naturally into a "consistent baseline" category — like protein intake or sleep — rather than something that requires cycle-specific cycling on/off.</p>

