    <!-- CAFFEINE INTERACTION -->
    <h2>Does Caffeine Affect Creatine Timing?</h2>

    <p>A frequent question from women who train in the morning with coffee or pre-workout caffeine: does caffeine reduce creatine effectiveness if taken together?</p>

    <p>The answer is mostly no, with a small caveat. A single 1996 study suggested caffeine might blunt creatine's ergogenic effects, but the result has not been consistently replicated. Subsequent research has found no meaningful interference at typical caffeine doses (100-200mg, equivalent to 1-2 cups of coffee). Most current sports nutrition reviews conclude that caffeine and creatine can be co-administered without significant interaction.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Practical guidance:</strong> Taking creatine with morning coffee, an energy drink, or a caffeinated pre-workout is fine for almost all women. If you want to be maximally cautious, separate creatine and caffeine by 30-60 minutes — but the interaction concern is largely outdated and the practical impact minimal.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- HOW TO ESTABLISH HABIT -->
    <h2>How to Build a Daily Creatine Habit That Sticks</h2>

    <p>Since consistency is the dominant variable in creatine results, the practical question is how to never miss a daily dose. The behavior science of habit formation gives clear guidance.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="anchor" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Anchor to Existing Habit</h3>
        <p>Pair creatine dosing with a daily activity you never skip — morning coffee, breakfast, brushing teeth, post-workout shake. The existing habit triggers the new one. This is the single most effective behavioral intervention for daily supplementation compliance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="eye" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Visible Storage</h3>
        <p>Keep creatine where you will see it at the trigger moment — coffee maker, breakfast counter, gym bag, bedside table. Out of sight equals out of mind. Visible storage drives compliance dramatically.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="package" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Choose Convenient Format</h3>
        <p>Powder requires mixing in water or food (more friction). Capsules require pill swallowing and 4-7 capsules per dose (more friction). Gummies require nothing — chew and done. Lower friction equals higher daily compliance, especially for women with busy mornings.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="calendar" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Track for 30 Days</h3>
        <p>Habits typically solidify after 30-66 days of consistent practice. Track daily dosing on a calendar or app for the first month. After that, the behavior usually becomes automatic and tracking is no longer necessary.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- VERDICT -->
    <div class="verdict">
      <h3>Our Verdict: Best Time = Most Reliable Time for You</h3>
      <p><strong>The "best time" to take creatine for women is whichever time you will reliably take it every single day.</strong> Post-workout has a marginal edge in research data, but the within-day timing differences are small (5-15%) compared to the consistency variable (50-200% effect on results).</p>
      <p>Practical recommendations:</p>
      <ul style="margin-left:20px;">
        <li><strong>Morning with breakfast</strong> for most women — pairs with consistent daily routine, easy to remember</li>
        <li><strong>Post-workout</strong> for women who train at consistent times daily — slight uptake advantage</li>
